        "last_activity_date": 1516977973,
        "creation_date": 1516977062,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Java cant adding object in list without generic",
        "body": "<p>I have those classes.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Flight {\n    public List&lt;FlightOffer&gt; flightOffers;\n}\n\npublic class Hotel&lt;T&gt; {\n    public List&lt;HotelOffer&gt; hotelOffers;\n    public T address\n}\n\npublic class FlightOffer extends BaseOffer{\n}\n\npublic class HotelOffer extends BaseOffer{\n}\n\npublic class BaseOffer{\n    public String id;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>flightOffers and hotelOffers returns a list.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Flight flightObject = new Flight();\nflightObject.flightOffers.add(new BaseOffer()); // not working \n//(add (FlightOffer) List  cannot be applied to (BaseOffer))\n\nHotel hotelObject = new Hotel&lt;String&gt;();\nhotelObject.hotelOffers.add(new BaseOffer()); // working\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>but if i convert <code>Flight<\/code> to <code>Flight&lt;T&gt;<\/code> its working, why?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 48463401,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "generics"
        ],
        "score": 4,
        "accepted_answer_id": 48463548,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 238,
        "last_edit_date": 1516977365
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/72baa38005eb8de126b2dd2e6fa1d660?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 319873,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 637853,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/637853/thomas",
                "reputation": 88895,
                "display_name": "Thomas",
                "accept_rate": 50
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 9,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1516977921,
            "creation_date": 1516977506,
            "body": "<p><code>List&lt;FlightOffer&gt; flightOffers<\/code> defines quite clearly what you can add to the list: instances of <code>FlightOffer<\/code>. <code>flightOffers.add(new BaseOffer());<\/code> hence can't work since a <code>BaseOffer<\/code> <em>is not<\/em> a <code>FlightOffer<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>So why does <code>hotelOffers.add(new BaseOffer());<\/code> work? Because you are disabling generic type checks by using the raw type <code>Hotel<\/code> in <code>Hotel hotelObject = new Hotel&lt;String&gt;();<\/code>. <\/p>\n\n<p>You should get a warning about that as well which conveys another lesson: don't ignore the warnings. The compiler doesn't know that something <em>will<\/em> fail but more often than not it \"guesses\" correctly and warns you about that.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Note what the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-4.html#jls-4.8\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JLS<\/a> states on raw types (in the first box of section 4.8):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Another implication of the rules above is that a generic inner class of a raw type can itself only be used as a raw type.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>That means that because <code>Hotel<\/code> is a raw type, every generic type inside it can also only be a raw type, i.e. <code>hotelOffers<\/code> is treated as if it were a raw <code>List<\/code> which allows any type of object (thus even this should work in your code <code>hotelObject.hotelOffers.add(\"I'm not a hotel offer\");<\/code>)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 48463548,
            "question_id": 48463401,
            "last_edit_date": 1516977921
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab7639c8c2d707deb0b8781bacb28058?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 444874,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 836967,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/836967/giancarlo-romeo",
                "reputation": 661,
                "display_name": "Giancarlo Romeo"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1516977973,
            "creation_date": 1516977320,
            "body": "<p>You're trying to add a <code>BaseOffer<\/code> object (superclass) in a <code>List<\/code> of <code>FlightOffer<\/code> (subclass) objects.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/IandI/subclasses.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/IandI/subclasses.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Flight flightObject = new Flight();\nflightObject.flightOffers.add(new FlightOffer());    // that's correct\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 48463484,
            "question_id": 48463401,
            "last_edit_date": 1516977973
        }
